\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Godly Sorrow:
\f4\b0  Focuses on the Cross. It mourns the fact that our sin cost Jesus His life.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 3. Confession\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0 \cf2 Confession is "agreeing with God" about our sin. It should be specific, not general. Instead of saying, "Lord, forgive my many sins," we say, "Lord, I was prideful in that meeting today, and I looked down on my colleague."\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 4. Shame (Humble Abhorrence)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0 \cf2 This isn't a toxic shame that leads to hiding, but a holy "blushing" before God. It is the realization that we have traded the Creator for the creature.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 5. Hatred of Sin\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0 \cf2 True repentance involves a shift in our affections. We don't just stop doing the sin because we have to; we begin to hate the sin because of what it does to our relationship with Jesus. We begin to see the "hook" inside the "bait."\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 6. Turning from Sin\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0 \cf2 This is the "pivot." It involves practical steps to walk in the opposite direction. If repentance is a change of mind, it must result in a change of life.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 \strokec2 III. The "How-To" of Fighting Sin\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs24 \cf2 For the new believer, "fighting sin" can feel like a losing battle if they rely on willpower alone. We must teach them the "Mortification of Sin."\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 1. Starve the Flesh, Feed the Spirit
\f4\b0 \
Romans 13:14 tells us to "make no provision for the flesh." If someone struggles with anger, they shouldn't spend all day consuming polarizing media. If they struggle with lust, they need digital boundaries. At the same time, they must "gorge" themselves on the Word of God and prayer.\

\f0\b 2. The Power of "Expulsive Affection"
\f4\b0 \
Thomas Chalmers wrote about the "expulsive power of a new affection." You don't stop loving sin by trying to hate it more; you stop loving sin by loving Jesus more. As the beauty of Christ increases in our sight, the "charms" of sin naturally fade.\

\f0\b 3. Use the "Care Covenant" Model
\f4\b0 \
In human relationships, sin often manifests as conflict. Teaching a new believer to respond with grace\'97declaring the other person as a "gift and not an enemy," owning hurtful words immediately, and listening before defending\'97is a practical outworking of a repentant heart (James 3).\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

